State MSM Profile: New Hampshire

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in New Hampshire

An estimated 14,122 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in New Hampshire in 2013, representing 0.3% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 507,277 adult men of New Hampshire, 2.8% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in New Hampshire resided in fringe counties of large metropolitan areas (48.2%). Including both central and fringe counties, 48.2% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and New Hampshire, 2013

MSM in New Hampshire Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in New Hampshire, Rockingham County had the largest population of MSM at 5,611, representing 39.7% of all MSM in the state. Rockingham County also had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in New Hampshire at 5.0%. This was greater than the percentage for New Hampshire as a whole, which was 2.8% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in New Hampshire Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Boston-Cambridge-Newton Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Boston-Cambridge-Newton MSA overlaps two states: Massachusetts and New Hampshire. The New Hampshire portion of the MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in New Hampshire at 6,803, or 48.2% of all MSM in the state and 7.4% of the 92,527 MSM in the MSA. Of the 160,560 adult men in the New Hampshire part of Boston-Cambridge-Newton, an estimated 4.2% were MSM. This was less than the percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA as a whole, which was 5.3% of adult men (92,527 out of 1,729,903).



Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Manchester-Nashua Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Manchester-Nashua MSA had a population of 3,175 MSM, or 22.5% of all MSM in New Hampshire. Of the 151,890 adult men in Manchester-Nashua, an estimated 2.1% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
